Plugin tools are namespaced to prevent collisions with builtins:
```rust
// In PluginManager::get_tools()
PluginTool::new(
    format!("plugin:{}:{}", plugin.manifest.plugin.name, tool_def.name),
    tool_def.description.clone(),
    tool_def.command.clone(),
    plugin.dir.clone(),
    tool_def.params.clone(),
)
```

The `plugin:` prefix is critical for security: it means a plugin can never masquerade as a built-in tool like `bash` or `file_write`. The permission classifier sees the full namespaced name, so plugin tools go through the same permission pipeline as everything else.

The key insight: Rust's `std::process::Command` does NOT invoke a shell. Arguments passed via `.arg()` are sent directly to the OS `exec` syscall as individual argv elements. Shell metacharacters (`$()`, backticks, `&&`, pipes) are treated as literal characters.

This is safe by construction, unlike Python's `subprocess.Popen(shell=True)` or C's `system()`.

```rust
use std::process::Command;
use std::path::PathBuf;

// SAFE: Command::arg passes the path as a single argv element.
// Even "$(whoami)" or "; rm -rf /" are literal strings, not executed.
fn spawn_with_model_path(path: &Path) -> std::io::Result<std::process::Output> {
    Command::new("python3")
        .arg("server.py")
        .arg("--model")
        .arg(path)  // Entire path is ONE argument, no shell expansion
        .output()
}

// UNSAFE: This invokes a shell. NEVER do this with untrusted input.
fn spawn_unsafe(path: &str) -> std::io::Result<std::process::Output> {
    Command::new("bash")
        .arg("-c")
        .arg(format!("python3 server.py --model {}", path))  // INJECTION!
        .output()
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn test_p0_shell_metacharacters_safe_with_arg() {
        // This path contains shell injection characters
        let dangerous = PathBuf::from("/tmp/models/; rm -rf /; echo pwned");
        // Command::arg sends it as literal argv -- no shell interprets it
        let cmd = Command::new("echo")
            .arg(dangerous.to_str().unwrap())
            .output()
            .unwrap();
        let output = String::from_utf8_lossy(&cmd.stdout);
        // The entire string appears as output, proving no shell execution
        assert!(output.contains("; rm -rf /"));
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_p0_backtick_injection_literal() {
        let path = PathBuf::from("/tmp/$(whoami)");
        let cmd = Command::new("echo")
            .arg(path.to_str().unwrap())
            .output()
            .unwrap();
        let output = String::from_utf8_lossy(&cmd.stdout);
        // $(whoami) appears literally, not expanded
        assert!(output.contains("$(whoami)"));
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_p0_null_byte_in_path_fails_spawn() {
        // Null bytes cause exec to fail at OS level
        let path = "/tmp/model\0malicious";
        let result = std::ffi::CString::new(path);
        assert!(result.is_err(), "CString rejects interior null bytes");
    }
}
```

Rules: (1) never use `bash -c` with string formatting on untrusted input, (2) always use `.arg()` to pass individual arguments, (3) for piping code to a subprocess, use stdin (`Stdio::piped()`) rather than constructing shell commands. The subprocess receives its arguments via the kernel's argv mechanism, bypassing any shell interpretation entirely.

```swift
@MainActor
class SerenaOrchestrator: ObservableObject {
    @Published private(set) var isProcessing = false
    @Published private(set) var lastProcessingType: ProcessingType?

    private let aiEngine: any AIEngine
    private let rtaiManager: RTAIManager
    private let configManager: ConfigManager

    enum ProcessingType {
        case rtai, adapter, standardLLM, mcp
    }

    func processInput(_ input: String, context: [Message] = [],
                      bypassRTAI: Bool = false) async throws -> String {
        isProcessing = true
        defer { isProcessing = false }

        // Route: RTAI first (if enabled and not bypassed)
        if !bypassRTAI && configManager.userConfig.rtaiEnabled
            && rtaiManager.isRTAITask(input) {
            return try await handleRTAITask(input, context: context)
        }
        return try await handleStandardLLMQuery(input, context: context)
    }

    private func handleRTAITask(_ input: String, context: [Message]) async throws -> String {
        lastProcessingType = .rtai
        do {
            return try await rtaiManager.handle(input)
        } catch {
            // Fallback to LLM - PRESERVE CONTEXT
            return try await handleStandardLLMQuery(input, context: context)
        }
    }

    private func handleStandardLLMQuery(_ input: String, context: [Message],
                                         bypassRTAI: Bool = false) async throws -> String {
        // Try RTAI bridge for high-confidence reflexive responses (0.85+)
        if !bypassRTAI {
            let rtaiResult = await RTAIBridge.shared.processText(input, context: context)
            if rtaiResult.success && rtaiResult.confidence > 0.85 {
                lastProcessingType = .rtai
                return rtaiResult.response
            }
        }

        guard aiEngine.isReady else {
            throw SerenaError.aiModelNotLoaded
        }

        // Standard LLM query
        do {
            lastProcessingType = .standardLLM
            return try await aiEngine.generateResponse(for: input, context: context)
        } catch {
            throw error
        }
    }
}
```

Key design decisions:
- `bypassRTAI` parameter for internal system prompts (summaries, etc.) that should always go to the LLM
- RTAI confidence threshold of 0.85 prevents low-quality reflexive responses from short-circuiting the LLM
- Context is preserved through the fallback chain - when RTAI fails, the LLM gets the full conversation history
- All state observation via `@Published` for SwiftUI binding
- `@MainActor` because UI state updates must happen on the main thread

Three reasons: update safety, permissions, and sandboxing.

1. **Update safety**: Bundled knowledge (medical facts, coding conventions, etc.) ships inside the app bundle and gets updated with app releases. User facts (wife's name, preferred language) are personal data. If they lived in the same files, an app update that replaces bundle resources would wipe user data. Separation means updates never touch user files.

2. **macOS permissions**: The app bundle (`Bundle.main.resourceURL`) is code-signed and read-only after installation. Writing to it would break the signature and trigger Gatekeeper warnings. Application Support (`~/Library/Application Support/`) is the designated writable location for per-user data.

3. **Sandboxing**: On sandboxed macOS apps, the app can only write to its container. Application Support is inside the container. The bundle is read-only. Trying to write to the bundle would throw a permission error.

The implementation creates user .ftai files on first launch if they don't exist:
```swift
private nonisolated func ensureUserFilesExistSync() {
    let userDataDir = appSupport.appendingPathComponent("Serena/rtai-user-data").path
    if !fileManager.fileExists(atPath: userDataDir) {
        try fileManager.createDirectory(atPath: userDataDir, withIntermediateDirectories: true)
    }
    // Create template files if missing...
}
```

This runs synchronously in `init()` so the files are guaranteed to exist before any async fact operations.

Use `matches!` macro for the first word and pattern-based checks for command content. Chain them with early returns from most dangerous to safest.

```rust
fn classify_single_bash(cmd: &str) -> PermissionTier {
    let trimmed = cmd.trim();
    let inner = strip_subshell(trimmed);

    // Check destructive patterns first (most dangerous)
    for pattern in DESTRUCTIVE_BASH_PATTERNS {
        if inner.starts_with(pattern) || inner.contains(&format!(" {pattern}")) {
            return PermissionTier::Destructive;
        }
    }

    // System path access in write commands
    let first_word = inner.split_whitespace().next().unwrap_or("");
    if matches!(first_word, "tee" | "cp" | "mv" | "mkdir" | "touch") {
        for prefix in SYSTEM_PATH_PREFIXES {
            if inner.contains(prefix) {
                return PermissionTier::Destructive;
            }
        }
    }

    // Check safe commands
    for safe in SAFE_BASH_COMMANDS {
        if inner == *safe
            || inner.starts_with(&format!("{safe} "))
            || inner.starts_with(&format!("{safe}\t"))
        {
            return PermissionTier::Safe;
        }
    }

    // Check write commands
    for write_cmd in WRITE_BASH_COMMANDS {
        if inner.starts_with(write_cmd) {
            return PermissionTier::Write;
        }
    }

    // Default: treat unknown as Write
    PermissionTier::Write
}
```

For compound commands (`ls && rm file`), split on operators and take the worst tier:
```rust
fn classify_bash(params: &Value) -> PermissionTier {
    let segments = split_compound_command(command);
    segments.iter()
        .map(|s| classify_single_bash(s))
        .fold(PermissionTier::Safe, worse_tier)
}
```

The order matters: check destructive first, safe second, write third, default to write. This ensures `sudo ls` is classified as Destructive (sudo matched), not Safe (ls matched).

You need two separate conversion paths because the wire formats differ significantly.

For Anthropic, the system message is extracted and sent as a top-level `system` field, not in the messages array. User and assistant messages use a `content` array with typed blocks:

```rust
fn convert_to_anthropic(&self, request: &ChatRequest) -> (Option<String>, Vec<serde_json::Value>) {
    let mut system = None;
    let mut messages = Vec::new();
    for msg in &request.messages {
        match msg.role {
            Role::System => { system = Some(msg.content.clone()); }
            Role::User => {
                messages.push(json!({"role": "user", "content": msg.content}));
            }
            Role::Assistant => {
                // Must include tool_use blocks alongside text
                let mut content = vec![json!({"type": "text", "text": msg.content})];
                if let Some(tcs) = &msg.tool_calls {
                    for tc in tcs {
                        content.push(json!({
                            "type": "tool_use", "id": tc.id,
                            "name": tc.name, "input": tc.arguments
                        }));
                    }
                }
                messages.push(json!({"role": "assistant", "content": content}));
            }
            Role::Tool => {
                messages.push(json!({
                    "role": "user",
                    "content": [{"type": "tool_result", "tool_use_id": msg.tool_call_id, "content": msg.content}]
                }));
            }
        }
    }
    (system, messages)
}
```

For OpenAI, it's simpler -- system stays in messages, tool results use the `tool` role.

Yes. Anthropic uses `input_schema` instead of `parameters`, and wraps differently:

```rust
fn anthropic_tool_def(t: &ToolDefinition) -> serde_json::Value {
    json!({
        "name": t.name,
        "description": t.description,
        "input_schema": t.parameters
    })
}
```

OpenAI wraps in a `function` object with a `type` field:

```rust
fn openai_tool_def(t: &ToolDefinition) -> OaiTool {
    OaiTool {
        tool_type: "function".to_string(),
        function: OaiToolDef {
            name: t.name.clone(),
            description: t.description.clone(),
            parameters: t.parameters.clone(),
        },
    }
}
```

Keep your internal `ToolDefinition` format neutral (just name/description/parameters as JSON Schema), and convert at the protocol boundary. This way adding a new provider only means writing new conversion functions.

Prune after a full index run:

```rust
impl SearchStore {
    pub fn prune_deleted_files(&self, root: &Path) -> Result<usize> {
        let mut stmt = self.conn.prepare(
            "SELECT DISTINCT file_path FROM chunks"
        )?;
        let stored_files: Vec<String> = stmt.query_map([], |row| row.get(0))?
            .collect::<Result<Vec<_>, _>>()?;

        let mut pruned = 0;
        for rel_path in &stored_files {
            let full_path = root.join(rel_path);
            if !full_path.exists() {
                self.delete_file(rel_path)?;
                pruned += 1;
            }
        }
        Ok(pruned)
    }

    pub fn delete_file(&self, file_path: &str) -> Result<()> {
        self.conn.execute(
            "DELETE FROM chunks WHERE file_path = ?1", [file_path]
        )?;
        Ok(())
    }
}
```

For incremental updates (single file changed), check existence first:
```rust
pub fn update_file(&mut self, file_path: &Path) -> Result<()> {
    let rel = file_path.strip_prefix(&self.project_root)
        .unwrap_or(file_path).to_string_lossy().to_string();
    if !file_path.exists() {
        self.store.delete_file(&rel)?;  // File deleted
        return Ok(());
    }
    let mtime = file_mtime(file_path);
    self.index_single_file(file_path, &rel, mtime)?;
    Ok(())
}
```

The full-project prune runs at the end of `index_project()` to catch files that were deleted while the indexer was running. The incremental `update_file` handles real-time file watching events.

Oversized payloads are a P2 resource exhaustion vulnerability. The attack scenario: a user (or a model) generates a 10MB message that gets stored in SQLite. Over multiple sessions, this bloats the database, consumes disk space, and slows queries. Worse, loading the session history into memory for context could OOM.

```rust
const MAX_MESSAGE_SIZE: usize = 1_024 * 1_024; // 1MB
const MAX_TOOL_CALL_JSON_SIZE: usize = 512 * 1_024; // 512KB

pub fn save_message(
    conn: &Connection,
    session_id: &str,
    role: &str,
    content: &str,
    tool_calls_json: Option<&str>,
) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    // Size limit on message content
    if content.len() > MAX_MESSAGE_SIZE {
        anyhow::bail!(
            "message content too large: {} bytes (max {})",
            content.len(),
            MAX_MESSAGE_SIZE
        );
    }

    // Size limit on tool call JSON
    if let Some(tc) = tool_calls_json {
        if tc.len() > MAX_TOOL_CALL_JSON_SIZE {
            anyhow::bail!(
                "tool call JSON too large: {} bytes (max {})",
                tc.len(),
                MAX_TOOL_CALL_JSON_SIZE
            );
        }
    }

    conn.execute(
        "INSERT INTO messages (session_id, role, content, tool_calls) VALUES (?1, ?2, ?3, ?4)",
        params![session_id, role, content, tool_calls_json],
    )?;
    Ok(())
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn test_p2_oversized_message_rejected() {
        let conn = Connection::open_in_memory().unwrap();
        conn.execute_batch(
            "CREATE TABLE messages (session_id TEXT, role TEXT, content TEXT, tool_calls TEXT)"
        ).unwrap();

        let large = "x".repeat(2 * 1024 * 1024); // 2MB
        let result = save_message(&conn, "s1", "user", &large, None);
        assert!(result.is_err(), "Oversized message must be rejected");
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_p2_normal_message_accepted() {
        let conn = Connection::open_in_memory().unwrap();
        conn.execute_batch(
            "CREATE TABLE messages (session_id TEXT, role TEXT, content TEXT, tool_calls TEXT)"
        ).unwrap();

        let normal = "x".repeat(1000);
        let result = save_message(&conn, "s1", "user", &normal, None);
        assert!(result.is_ok());
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_p2_oversized_tool_calls_rejected() {
        let conn = Connection::open_in_memory().unwrap();
        conn.execute_batch(
            "CREATE TABLE messages (session_id TEXT, role TEXT, content TEXT, tool_calls TEXT)"
        ).unwrap();

        let large_json = format!("{{\"data\": \"{}\"}}", "x".repeat(1_000_000));
        let result = save_message(&conn, "s1", "assistant", "msg", Some(&large_json));
        assert!(result.is_err(), "Oversized tool call JSON must be rejected");
    }
}
```

Set limits that are generous enough for normal usage (1MB messages, 512KB tool calls) but prevent abuse. Log rejections so you can tune the limits based on real usage patterns.

This has a P0 GBNF grammar injection vulnerability. The attack scenario: a plugin registers a tool with name `" | ws | "` (containing GBNF syntax). When interpolated, the grammar becomes:

```
tool-name ::= "bash"  | "" | ws | ""  | "file_read"
```

The injected `| ws |` creates an alternation that matches any whitespace, meaning the model can use ANY string as a tool name. The constraint grammar becomes useless.

Another vector: a tool name containing `\n` injects a new grammar rule on a separate line.

Fix: validate tool names against `[a-zA-Z0-9_]+` before including them in the grammar. Skip invalid names, and if no valid names remain, return an error.

```rust
pub fn build_tool_call_grammar(tool_names: &[&str]) -> anyhow::Result<String> {
    let valid: Vec<&&str> = tool_names.iter()
        .filter(|n| !n.is_empty() && n.chars().all(|c| c.is_ascii_alphanumeric() || c == '_'))
        .collect();

    if valid.is_empty() {
        anyhow::bail!("no valid tool names for grammar generation");
    }

    let names: String = valid.iter()
        .map(|n| format!("\"{}\" ", n))
        .collect::<Vec<_>>()
        .join("| ");
    Ok(format!("tool-name ::= {}\n", names))
}

#[test]
fn test_p0_grammar_injection_blocked() {
    assert!(build_tool_call_grammar(&["\" | ws | \""]).is_err());
    let g = build_tool_call_grammar(&["bash", "\" | ws | \""]).unwrap();
    assert!(g.contains("\"bash\""));
    assert!(!g.contains("ws"), "Injection payload must not appear in grammar");
}
```

