Use compiled regex patterns stored in a `OnceLock` for one-time initialization, each tagged with a fact key and confidence:

```rust
struct PatternDef {
    re: Regex,
    key: &'static str,
    confidence: f32,
}

fn patterns() -> &'static Vec<PatternDef> {
    static PATTERNS: OnceLock<Vec<PatternDef>> = OnceLock::new();
    PATTERNS.get_or_init(|| vec![
        PatternDef { re: Regex::new(r"(?i)\bmy name is\s+(.+?)(?:[.;!]\s|$)").unwrap(),
                     key: "user_name", confidence: 0.95 },
        PatternDef { re: Regex::new(r"(?i)\bi(?:'m| am) an?\s+(.+?)(?:[.;!]\s|$)").unwrap(),
                     key: "user_role", confidence: 0.8 },
        PatternDef { re: Regex::new(r"(?i)\b(?:don't|never|avoid)\s+(.+?)(?:[.;!]\s|$)").unwrap(),
                     key: "constraint", confidence: 0.85 },
    ])
}

pub struct FactExtractor;

impl FactExtractor {
    pub fn extract_facts(&self, text: &str) -> Vec<ExtractedFact> {
        let mut facts = Vec::new();
        for pat in patterns() {
            for cap in pat.re.captures_iter(text) {
                if let Some(m) = cap.get(1) {
                    let value = clean_value(m.as_str());
                    if !value.is_empty() {
                        facts.push(ExtractedFact::new(pat.key, value, pat.confidence));
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        facts
    }
}
```

Multiple matches from the same pattern are all returned (e.g., two constraints in one message). Confidence scores let downstream consumers prioritize: 0.95 for names (high reliability), 0.7 for preferences (might be casual). The `OnceLock` ensures regex compilation happens exactly once across all calls.

What's wrong with this code that tries to build a streaming parser?

```rust
struct Parser {
    buffer: String,
    in_tag: bool,
}

impl Parser {
    fn feed(&mut self, chunk: &str) -> Vec<Event> {
        self.buffer += chunk;
        let mut events = vec![];
        if let Some(pos) = self.buffer.find("<tag>") {
            events.push(Event::Text(self.buffer[..pos].to_string()));
            self.buffer = self.buffer[pos + 5..].to_string();
            self.in_tag = true;
        }
        events
    }
}
```

Two critical bugs:

1. **Partial tag at buffer end is not handled.** If chunk ends with `"<ta"`, the next chunk `"g>"` completes the tag, but `find("<tag>")` won't match on the first call. The `"<ta"` will be emitted as Text, then `"g>"` arrives and is also emitted as text -- the tag is silently swallowed.

2. **Only processes one tag per `feed()` call.** If two tags arrive in one chunk, the second is ignored until the next `feed()`.

**Fixed with safe-emit-length and loop:**
```rust
impl Parser {
    fn feed(&mut self, chunk: &str) -> Vec<Event> {
        self.buffer.push_str(chunk);
        let mut events = Vec::new();

        loop {
            if self.in_tag {
                if let Some(end) = self.buffer.find("</tag>") {
                    let body = self.buffer[..end].to_string();
                    events.push(Event::TagComplete(body));
                    self.buffer = self.buffer[end + 6..].to_string();
                    self.in_tag = false;
                    continue; // Check for more content
                } else {
                    break; // Need more data
                }
            } else {
                if let Some(start) = self.buffer.find("<tag>") {
                    if start > 0 {
                        events.push(Event::Text(self.buffer[..start].to_string()));
                    }
                    self.buffer = self.buffer[start + 5..].to_string();
                    self.in_tag = true;
                    continue;
                } else {
                    // Emit text that CAN'T be part of a partial tag
                    let safe = self.safe_emit_len("<tag>");
                    if safe > 0 {
                        events.push(Event::Text(self.buffer[..safe].to_string()));
                        self.buffer = self.buffer[safe..].to_string();
                    }
                    break;
                }
            }
        }
        events
    }

    fn safe_emit_len(&self, tag: &str) -> usize {
        let buf = self.buffer.as_bytes();
        let tag_bytes = tag.as_bytes();
        for suffix_start in (1..=buf.len().min(tag_bytes.len())).rev() {
            let suffix = &buf[buf.len().saturating_sub(suffix_start)..];
            if tag_bytes.starts_with(suffix) {
                return buf.len() - suffix.len();
            }
        }
        buf.len()
    }
}
```

The `safe_emit_len` function checks if the buffer ends with a prefix of the tag. If the buffer ends with `"<ta"`, that's a prefix of `"<tag>"`, so we hold those 3 bytes back.

Three components: the tool definition (so the model can request spawning), validation, and tool filtering.

```rust
pub const SUBAGENT_SYSTEM_PROMPT: &str = "\
You are a focused subagent. Complete the task thoroughly and provide a clear summary. \
Do not ask questions -- work autonomously.";

pub const SUBAGENT_MAX_ITERATIONS: usize = 30;

pub fn validate_params(params: &Value) -> Option<String> {
    let task = params["task"].as_str().unwrap_or("");
    if task.is_empty() { return Some("Missing required parameter: task".into()); }
    if task.len() > 10_000 { return Some("Task too long".into()); }
    if task.contains('\0') { return Some("Null bytes not allowed".into()); }

    if let Some(tools) = params["tools"].as_array() {
        for t in tools {
            if let Some(name) = t.as_str() {
                if name == "agent_spawn" {
                    return Some("Recursion not allowed".into());
                }
                if name.contains('/') || name.contains("..") {
                    return Some(format!("Invalid tool name: {name}"));
                }
            }
        }
    }
    None
}

pub fn filter_tools(all_tools: &[ToolDefinition], requested: Option<&[String]>) -> Vec<ToolDefinition> {
    all_tools.iter().filter(|t| {
        if t.name == "agent_spawn" { return false; } // Always exclude
        if let Some(req) = requested {
            return req.iter().any(|r| r == &t.name);
        }
        true
    }).cloned().collect()
}
```

Security invariants: (1) `agent_spawn` is always stripped from subagent tools to prevent recursion bombs. (2) Tool names are validated against path traversal. (3) Task length is capped to prevent context stuffing. (4) The subagent gets a fresh message history (no parent context leakage). (5) Execution is handled as a special case in the agent loop, not by the tool's `execute()` method.

Feed the input one character at a time -- this is the hardest case for any streaming parser because every boundary is tested.

```rust
#[test]
fn test_single_char_chunks() {
    let mut parser = StreamingToolCallParser::new();
    let input = "<tool_call>\n<function=bash>\n<parameter=command>ls</parameter>\n</function>\n</tool_call>";

    let mut all = Vec::new();
    for ch in input.chars() {
        all.extend(parser.feed(&ch.to_string()));
    }
    all.extend(parser.flush());

    let complete: Vec<&ParsedToolCall> = all.iter()
        .filter_map(|e| match e {
            StreamEvent::ToolCallComplete(c) => Some(c),
            _ => None,
        })
        .collect();

    assert_eq!(complete.len(), 1);
    assert_eq!(complete[0].name, "bash");
}
```

Also test the split-across-chunks case:
