Client-side rate limit storage requires tamper detection because users can edit the data to reset their counter. The attack scenario: a free-tier user opens the storage file, deletes their message timestamps, and the rate limiter thinks they have zero messages sent. HMAC signing prevents this.

```rust
use hmac::{Hmac, Mac};
use sha2::Sha256;

type HmacSha256 = Hmac<Sha256>;

const WINDOW_SECS: f64 = 24.0 * 60.0 * 60.0;
const MAX_IN_WINDOW: usize = 20;

pub struct SignedCounter {
    key: [u8; 32],
}

impl SignedCounter {
    pub fn new(key: [u8; 32]) -> Self {
        Self { key }
    }

    /// Serialize timestamps with HMAC: "ts1,ts2,...|hex_signature"
    pub fn serialize(&self, timestamps: &[f64]) -> String {
        let payload: String = timestamps.iter()
            .map(|t| t.to_string())
            .collect::<Vec<_>>()
            .join(",");
        let sig = self.sign(payload.as_bytes());
        format!("{}|{}", payload, sig)
    }

    /// Deserialize and verify. Returns None if tampered or malformed.
    pub fn deserialize(&self, stored: &str) -> Option<Vec<f64>> {
        let (payload, sig) = stored.split_once('|')?;
        self.verify(payload.as_bytes(), sig).ok()?;

        let timestamps: Vec<f64> = payload.split(',')
            .filter(|s| !s.is_empty())
            .filter_map(|s| s.parse::<f64>().ok())
            .filter(|t| !t.is_nan() && !t.is_infinite() && *t > 0.0)
            .collect();
        Some(timestamps)
    }

    /// Count messages in the rolling window.
    pub fn messages_in_window(&self, stored: &str, now: f64) -> usize {
        let cutoff = now - WINDOW_SECS;
        self.deserialize(stored)
            .map(|ts| ts.iter().filter(|&&t| t > cutoff).count())
            .unwrap_or(0)
    }

    fn sign(&self, data: &[u8]) -> String {
        let mut mac = HmacSha256::new_from_slice(&self.key).unwrap();
        mac.update(data);
        hex::encode(mac.finalize().into_bytes())
    }

    fn verify(&self, data: &[u8], sig_hex: &str) -> Result<(), ()> {
        let mut mac = HmacSha256::new_from_slice(&self.key).unwrap();
        mac.update(data);
        let sig = hex::decode(sig_hex).map_err(|_| ())?;
        mac.verify_slice(&sig).map_err(|_| ())
    }
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn test_roundtrip() {
        let counter = SignedCounter::new([0x42; 32]);
        let ts = vec![1000.0, 2000.0, 3000.0];
        let stored = counter.serialize(&ts);
        let loaded = counter.deserialize(&stored).unwrap();
        assert_eq!(loaded, ts);
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_tampered_payload_rejected() {
        let counter = SignedCounter::new([0x42; 32]);
        let stored = counter.serialize(&[1000.0, 2000.0]);
        let tampered = stored.replacen("1000", "9999", 1);
        assert!(counter.deserialize(&tampered).is_none());
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_fake_hmac_rejected() {
        let counter = SignedCounter::new([0x42; 32]);
        let fake = "1000.0,2000.0|deadbeef";
        assert!(counter.deserialize(fake).is_none());
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_malformed_no_pipe_rejected() {
        let counter = SignedCounter::new([0x42; 32]);
        assert!(counter.deserialize("no_pipe_separator").is_none());
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_nan_timestamps_filtered() {
        let counter = SignedCounter::new([0x42; 32]);
        // If somehow NaN got serialized, it should be filtered on load
        let stored = counter.serialize(&[1000.0]);
        let loaded = counter.deserialize(&stored).unwrap();
        for t in &loaded {
            assert!(!t.is_nan());
            assert!(!t.is_infinite());
            assert!(*t > 0.0);
        }
    }
}
```

The HMAC key should be derived from a device-specific secret (hardware ID, Keychain, etc.) so it's not trivially extractable. The `filter` on deserialization catches NaN/Infinity/negative values that could corrupt window calculations.

Fall back to a sliding window with overlap:

```rust
fn sliding_window_chunks(file_path: &str, lines: &[&str]) -> Vec<CodeChunk> {
    const WINDOW: usize = 40;
    const OVERLAP: usize = 10;
    let step = WINDOW.saturating_sub(OVERLAP).max(1);

    let mut chunks = Vec::new();
    let mut start = 0;

    while start < lines.len() {
        let end = (start + WINDOW).min(lines.len());
        let content = lines[start..end].join("\n");
        if !content.trim().is_empty() {
            chunks.push(CodeChunk {
                file_path: file_path.to_string(),
                chunk_type: ChunkType::Block,
                symbol_name: None,
                start_line: (start + 1) as u32,
                end_line: end as u32,
                content,
            });
        }
        if end == lines.len() { break; }
        start += step;
    }
    chunks
}
```

The 10-line overlap ensures that content near chunk boundaries isn't lost -- a function definition that starts at line 38 would appear in both the first chunk (lines 1-40) and the second chunk (lines 31-70). The embedding model can match queries against either occurrence.

Choose the boundary detector first, only fall back to sliding window when no patterns match. This handles config files, markdown, plain text, and languages the boundary detector doesn't know about.

Extra JSON fields are a parameter injection attack vector. The scenario: the model outputs a tool call with extra fields like `"admin": true, "sudo": true, "escalate_privileges": true`. If these fields are passed through to the tool executor without filtering, and if any downstream code checks for these keys, the model can escalate its own permissions.

```rust
use serde_json::Value;
use std::collections::HashMap;

pub fn parse_hermes_json(input: &str) -> Vec<ParsedToolCall> {
    let re = regex::Regex::new(r"<tool_call>\s*([\s\S]*?)\s*</tool_call>").unwrap();
    let mut calls = Vec::new();

    for cap in re.captures_iter(input) {
        let json_str = cap.get(1).unwrap().as_str().trim();
        if let Ok(val) = serde_json::from_str::<Value>(json_str) {
            let name = match val.get("name").and_then(|n| n.as_str()) {
                Some(n) => n.to_string(),
                None => continue, // Skip entries without a name
            };

            // SECURITY: Only extract "arguments" field. Discard everything else.
            // This prevents "admin", "sudo", "privilege" fields from leaking through.
            let arguments = match val.get("arguments") {
                Some(Value::Object(map)) => {
                    map.iter()
                        .map(|(k, v)| (k.clone(), v.clone()))
                        .collect::<HashMap<String, Value>>()
                }
                Some(Value::String(s)) => {
                    // Model sent arguments as string instead of object
                    let mut map = HashMap::new();
                    map.insert("_raw".to_string(), Value::String(s.clone()));
                    map
                }
                _ => HashMap::new(),
            };

            calls.push(ParsedToolCall {
                name,
                arguments,
                raw_text: json_str.to_string(),
            });
        }
    }
    calls
}

#[test]
fn test_p0_extra_fields_discarded() {
    let input = r#"<tool_call>
{"name": "file_read", "arguments": {"path": "/safe.txt"}, "admin": true, "sudo": true}
</tool_call>"#;

    let calls = parse_hermes_json(input);
    assert_eq!(calls.len(), 1);
    assert_eq!(calls[0].name, "file_read");
    assert!(!calls[0].arguments.contains_key("admin"), "Extra field 'admin' must be discarded");
    assert!(!calls[0].arguments.contains_key("sudo"), "Extra field 'sudo' must be discarded");
}

#[test]
fn test_p0_arguments_as_string_handled() {
    let input = r#"<tool_call>
{"name": "bash", "arguments": "rm -rf /"}
</tool_call>"#;

    let calls = parse_hermes_json(input);
    assert_eq!(calls.len(), 1);
    assert!(calls[0].arguments.contains_key("_raw"));
    // The string arguments should fail schema validation for "bash"
    // because "command" (required) is missing
}
```

The principle: parse only the fields you expect (`name` and `arguments`), discard everything else. This is allowlist-based parsing, not blocklist-based. You don't need to know what dangerous fields might exist -- you just ignore everything that isn't on the allowlist.

