DSL injection is analogous to SQL injection but for your custom rule language. The attack scenario: your evolution system generates rules by interpolating tool names, error messages, and project names into DSL templates. If any of these contain DSL metacharacters (quotes, braces, newlines), they can inject additional rule directives.

Example: error message `permission denied\n  reject "block_everything"\n}` breaks out of a string literal and injects a `reject` directive.

```rust
/// Sanitize a value for safe interpolation into FTAI DSL rule text.
/// Removes or escapes all characters that could alter rule structure.
pub fn sanitize_for_dsl(value: &str) -> String {
    let mut s = value.to_string();

    // 1. Escape backslashes FIRST (before escaping quotes)
    s = s.replace('\\', "\\\\");

    // 2. Escape double quotes
    s = s.replace('"', "\\\"");

    // 3. Remove newlines and carriage returns (structure-breaking)
    s = s.replace('\n', " ");
    s = s.replace('\r', "");

    // 4. Remove braces (could close/open rule blocks)
    s = s.replace('{', "");
    s = s.replace('}', "");

    // 5. Truncate to prevent rule bloat
    if s.len() > 200 {
        s.truncate(200);
    }

    s
}

/// Validate a tool name for use in DSL identifiers.
/// Only alphanumeric, hyphen, underscore allowed.
pub fn validate_dsl_identifier(name: &str) -> anyhow::Result<String> {
    if name.is_empty() {
        anyhow::bail!("empty identifier");
    }
    if !name.chars().all(|c| c.is_alphanumeric() || c == '-' || c == '_') {
        anyhow::bail!("identifier contains disallowed characters: {:?}", name);
    }
    Ok(name.to_string())
}

/// Generate a failure rule with sanitized error message.
pub fn generate_failure_rule(tool_name: &str, error_msg: &str, id: &str) -> anyhow::Result<String> {
    let safe_tool = validate_dsl_identifier(tool_name)?;
    let safe_error = sanitize_for_dsl(error_msg);
    let safe_id = validate_dsl_identifier(id)?;

    Ok(format!(
        "rule evo-fail-{safe_tool}-{safe_id} {{\n\
         \x20 scope \"*\"\n\
         \x20 on tool_call\n\
         \x20 when tool(\"{safe_tool}\")\n\
         \x20 reject \"Repeated failure: {safe_error}\"\n\
         }}"
    ))
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn test_p0_error_message_injection_blocked() {
        let evil = "permission denied\n  reject \"block_everything\"\n}";
        let rule = generate_failure_rule("bash", evil, "abc123").unwrap();
        let reject_count = rule.lines()
            .filter(|l| l.trim().starts_with("reject"))
            .count();
        assert_eq!(reject_count, 1, "Only one reject directive should exist");
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_p0_tool_name_injection_blocked() {
        let evil = "file_read\")\n  reject \"all\"";
        assert!(validate_dsl_identifier(evil).is_err());
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_p0_backslash_quote_chain() {
        let evil = r#"path\"  reject "pwned"#;
        let sanitized = sanitize_for_dsl(evil);
        // After sanitization, no unescaped quotes should remain
        assert!(!sanitized.contains("reject"));
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_safe_values_work() {
        let rule = generate_failure_rule("file_read", "file not found", "abc123").unwrap();
        assert!(rule.starts_with("rule "));
        assert!(rule.contains("file not found"));
        let open = rule.chars().filter(|c| *c == '{').count();
        let close = rule.chars().filter(|c| *c == '}').count();
        assert_eq!(open, close, "Braces must be balanced");
    }
}
```

The order of escaping matters critically: backslashes before quotes. If reversed, `\"` becomes `\\"` which is an escaped backslash followed by a bare quote, breaking out of the string.

Unicode boundary issues are a P2 denial-of-service vulnerability. The attack scenario: a function slices a string at a byte offset that falls in the middle of a multi-byte UTF-8 character, causing a panic. In Rust, string slicing panics on invalid char boundaries.

Example: the function checks the last 80 bytes of a string:
```rust
// DANGEROUS: panics if byte (len-80) is mid-character
let tail = &text[text.len() - 80..];
```

For CJK text where each character is 3 bytes, byte offset 80 from the end almost certainly lands mid-character.

Fix: use `char_indices()` to find safe boundaries:

```rust
/// Get the last N characters (not bytes) of a string, safely.
fn safe_tail(s: &str, char_count: usize) -> &str {
    let char_start = s.chars().count().saturating_sub(char_count);
    s.char_indices()
        .nth(char_start)
        .map(|(byte_idx, _)| &s[byte_idx..])
        .unwrap_or(s)
}

/// Alternative: find the nearest char boundary at or after a byte offset.
fn safe_byte_tail(s: &str, max_bytes: usize) -> &str {
    if s.len() <= max_bytes {
        return s;
    }
    let target = s.len() - max_bytes;
    // Walk forward to find a valid char boundary
    let start = (target..s.len())
        .find(|&i| s.is_char_boundary(i))
        .unwrap_or(s.len());
    &s[start..]
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn test_p2_cjk_boundary_no_panic() {
        // Each CJK char is 3 bytes. 30 chars = 90 bytes.
        let cjk = "\u{4e00}".repeat(30);
        let tail = safe_tail(&cjk, 10);
        assert_eq!(tail.chars().count(), 10);
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_p2_byte_tail_cjk_no_panic() {
        let cjk = "\u{4e00}".repeat(30);
        let tail = safe_byte_tail(&cjk, 80);
        // Should not panic, and result should be valid UTF-8
        assert!(tail.len() <= 80 + 2); // might overshoot by up to 2 bytes for alignment
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_p2_emoji_boundary() {
        let emoji = "\u{1F600}".repeat(25); // 4 bytes each = 100 bytes
        let tail = safe_byte_tail(&emoji, 80);
        assert!(!tail.is_empty());
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_short_string_returns_full() {
        let short = "hello";
        assert_eq!(safe_tail(short, 100), "hello");
        assert_eq!(safe_byte_tail(short, 100), "hello");
    }
}
```

Rule: never use `&s[byte_offset..]` unless you've verified `s.is_char_boundary(byte_offset)`. Prefer `chars()` or `char_indices()` for character-level operations. In security-sensitive code, a panic is a denial of service.

