    const CREATE_BREAKAWAY_FROM_JOB: u32 = 0x01000000;
    cmd.creation_flags(CREATE_BREAKAWAY_FROM_JOB);
}
```

The `CREATE_BREAKAWAY_FROM_JOB` flag on Windows allows child process management (killing timed-out processes). On Unix, the timeout is the primary guard. Both platforms pass the entire command string as a single argument to the shell -- metacharacters are intentionally live because this IS a shell tool.

For simple, well-defined XML-like formats (not arbitrary HTML/XML), regex is fine and avoids pulling in a full XML parser.

```rust
fn parse_tool_call_body(&self, body: &str) -> Option<ParsedToolCall> {
    let func_re = regex::Regex::new(r"(?s)<function=([^>]+)>(.*?)</function>").ok()?;
    let param_re = regex::Regex::new(r"(?s)<parameter=([^>]+)>(.*?)</parameter>").ok()?;

    let func_cap = func_re.captures(body)?;
    let func_name = func_cap.get(1)?.as_str().trim().to_string();
    let func_body = func_cap.get(2)?.as_str();

    let mut args = HashMap::new();
    for param_cap in param_re.captures_iter(func_body) {
        let key = param_cap.get(1).unwrap().as_str().trim().to_string();
        let val = param_cap.get(2).unwrap().as_str();
        // Try JSON parse, fall back to string
        let json_val = serde_json::from_str(val.trim())
            .unwrap_or_else(|_| serde_json::Value::String(val.to_string()));
        args.insert(key, json_val);
    }

    Some(ParsedToolCall {
        name: func_name,
        arguments: args,
        raw_text: format!("<tool_call>{body}</tool_call>"),
    })
}
```

This works because the format is controlled (Qwen 3.5 output), not arbitrary user XML. Key patterns:
- `(?s)` flag makes `.` match newlines (parameter values can span lines)
- `(.*?)` non-greedy match -- stops at first closing tag
- `[^>]+` for attribute values -- can't contain `>`
- `serde_json::from_str` with fallback to `String` -- handles both JSON values and plain text

When to NOT use regex: arbitrary nested XML, user-controlled HTML, documents with CDATA sections.

No. The parser should NOT block dangerous commands. This is a defense-in-depth architecture question with a clear answer: separate parsing (format) from policy (security).

The parser's job is to convert the model's output format (XML, JSON, etc.) into structured `ParsedToolCall` objects. It is format-agnostic and should parse ANY syntactically valid tool call regardless of content.

The validator and permissions layers enforce security:
- **Validator**: checks tool name against registry, validates parameter types against schema, rejects unknown tools
- **Permissions/Classifier**: checks for dangerous commands (`rm -rf /`), blocked paths (`/etc/passwd`, `~/.ssh/`), and requires user approval for risky operations

```rust
// Parser: format-only, no policy
fn parse_tool_calls(input: &str) -> Vec<ParsedToolCall> { /* ... */ }

// Validator: schema enforcement
fn validate(call: &ParsedToolCall) -> ValidationResult { /* ... */ }

// Permissions: safety policy
fn hard_block_check(tool: &str, params: &Value) -> Option<String> { /* ... */ }

// Full pipeline test:
#[test]
fn test_p0_full_pipeline_dangerous_bash_blocked() {
    // Parser accepts it (format is valid)
    let calls = parse_tool_calls("<tool_call>\n<function=bash>\n<parameter=command>rm -rf /</parameter>\n</function>\n</tool_call>");
    assert_eq!(calls.len(), 1);

    // Validator accepts it (schema is valid: command is a string)
    let v = make_validator();
    assert_eq!(v.validate(&calls[0]), ValidationResult::Valid);

    // Permissions layer blocks it (destructive command)
    let block = hard_block_check("bash", &json!({"command": "rm -rf /"}));
    assert!(block.is_some(), "Permissions must hard-block rm -rf /");
}
```

Why this separation matters:
1. The parser can be tested independently against format edge cases (chunk boundaries, nested tags, unicode) without worrying about security policy
2. Security policy is centralized in one layer, not scattered across parser/validator/executor
3. New tools get security enforcement automatically -- they go through the same permissions pipeline
4. The parser doesn't need updating when security policy changes

```rust
pub fn load_memory_context(project_path: &Path) -> Option<String> {
    let mut parts = Vec::new();

    // Global memories (~/.ftai/memory/)
    if let Ok(global_dir) = crate::config::global_config_dir() {
        let global_memory_dir = global_dir.join("memory");
        if let Some(content) = load_memory_layer(&global_memory_dir) {
            parts.push(format!("## Global Memory\n{content}"));
        }
    }

    // Project memories (<project>/.ftai/memory/)
    let project_memory_dir = project_path.join(".ftai").join("memory");
    if let Some(content) = load_memory_layer(&project_memory_dir) {
        parts.push(format!("## Project Memory\n{content}"));
    }

    // User-specific project memories (~/.ftai/projects/<encoded>/memory/)
    if let Ok(project_dir) = crate::config::project_config_dir(project_path) {
        let user_project_memory = project_dir.join("memory");
        if let Some(content) = load_memory_layer(&user_project_memory) {
            parts.push(format!("## User Project Memory\n{content}"));
        }
    }

    if parts.is_empty() { None }
    else { Some(parts.join("\n---\n")) }
}

fn load_memory_layer(dir: &Path) -> Option<String> {
    if !dir.exists() { return None; }
    let mut entries = Vec::new();

    if let Ok(files) = read_memory_dir(dir, None) {
        for (name, content) in files {
            if name == "MEMORY" {
                // Legacy format: include as-is
                if !content.trim().is_empty() { entries.push(content); }
                continue;
            }
            if !content.trim().is_empty() {
                entries.push(format!("### {name}\n{content}"));
            }
        }
    }

    if entries.is_empty() { None }
    else { Some(entries.join("\n")) }
}

pub fn strip_frontmatter(content: &str) -> &str {
    if !content.starts_with("---") { return content; }
    if let Some(end) = content[3..].find("---") {
        let after = &content[end + 6..];
        after.trim_start_matches('\n')
    } else {
        content
    }
}
```

Three layers give different scoping:
- **Global**: preferences that apply everywhere ("User prefers Rust", "Always use snake_case")
- **Project**: facts about this codebase ("Uses PostgreSQL", "JWT with RS256")
- **User-project**: personal overrides for shared repos (not committed to git)

The legacy `MEMORY.md` format (bullet-point list) is supported for backward compatibility but new memories use individual files with YAML frontmatter for categorization.

Buffer incoming bytes and track how much has been consumed:

```rust
let mut bytes = Vec::new();

while let Some(chunk) = stream.next().await {
    let chunk = chunk.context("Stream read error")?;
    bytes.extend_from_slice(&chunk);

    let text = String::from_utf8_lossy(&bytes);
    let mut consumed = 0;

    for line in text.lines() {
        consumed += line.len() + 1;  // +1 for newline

        if let Some(data) = line.strip_prefix("data: ") {
            // Process the SSE event data...
        }
    }

    // Only discard bytes we've fully processed
    bytes = bytes[consumed.min(bytes.len())..].to_vec();
}
```

The critical detail is `consumed.min(bytes.len())`. Without the `min`, you'd panic if `consumed` exceeds the buffer length (which can happen due to lossy UTF-8 conversion changing byte counts). The remaining bytes after truncation might be: (1) a partial line that hasn't received its newline yet, (2) partial UTF-8 bytes at the chunk boundary, or (3) nothing if the chunk ended on a line boundary. The next iteration will extend these bytes with the next chunk and try again.

This pattern works identically for both OpenAI (`data: {...}\ndata: [DONE]`) and Anthropic (`event: type\ndata: {...}`) SSE formats.

The FolkTech red test methodology is a structured approach to security testing that follows this cycle:

1. **Identify the attack vector** -- what could go wrong? (injection, path traversal, auth bypass, etc.)
2. **Write the test first** -- the test must describe the attack scenario
3. **Assert the defense** -- verify the system handles the attack safely
4. **Fix if failing** -- implement the defense
5. **Verify the fix** -- re-run to confirm

P0 (never-skip) categories:
- Input injection (SQL, command, tool call)
- Path traversal (`../../../etc/passwd`)
- Auth bypass (missing permission checks)
- LLM output injection (model output containing control sequences)

