For structs with many optional fields, the builder pattern shines:
```rust
pub struct ToolExecution {
    pub cancel: CancelToken,
    pub progress_rx: mpsc::Receiver<ToolProgress>,
    pub timeout: Option<Duration>,
    pub max_output: Option<usize>,
}

pub struct ToolExecutionBuilder {
    timeout: Option<Duration>,
    max_output: Option<usize>,
}

impl ToolExecutionBuilder {
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        Self { timeout: None, max_output: None }
    }

    pub fn timeout(mut self, d: Duration) -> Self {
        self.timeout = Some(d);
        self
    }

    pub fn max_output(mut self, n: usize) -> Self {
        self.max_output = Some(n);
        self
    }

    pub fn build(self) -> ToolExecution {
        let cancel = CancelToken::new();
        let (_tx, rx) = mpsc::channel(64);
        ToolExecution {
            cancel,
            progress_rx: rx,
            timeout: self.timeout,
            max_output: self.max_output,
        }
    }
}
```

Rule of thumb: if your struct has 2-3 required fields, just use struct literals. Builder pattern pays off at 4+ optional fields. Don't over-engineer.

Test both the positive case (rule blocks the call) and negative case (rule allows safe calls). This is the two-stage approach.

```rust
#[test]
fn test_rules_block_tool_execution() {
    let mut engine = RulesEngine::new();
    engine.load(r#"
rule "block-destructive" {
  on tool:bash
  reject matches(command, "rm -rf")
  reason "Destructive commands need confirmation"
}
"#).unwrap();

    // STAGE 1: Dangerous command should be REJECTED
    let mut ctx = EvalContext::new(RuleEvent::Tool("bash".to_string()));
    ctx.set_str("command", "rm -rf /important/data");
    let result = engine.evaluate(&ctx, None);
    assert!(matches!(result, RuleAction::Reject(_)),
        "Expected tool call to be rejected by rule");
}

#[test]
fn test_rules_allow_safe_bash() {
    let mut engine = RulesEngine::new();
    engine.load(r#"
rule "block-destructive" {
  on tool:bash
  reject matches(command, "rm -rf")
  reason "Destructive commands need confirmation"
}
"#).unwrap();

    // STAGE 2: Safe command should be ALLOWED
    let mut ctx = EvalContext::new(RuleEvent::Tool("bash".to_string()));
    ctx.set_str("command", "ls -la");
    let result = engine.evaluate(&ctx, None);
    assert!(matches!(result, RuleAction::Allow),
        "Expected safe command to be allowed");
}
```

Always test both sides: if you only test that dangerous commands are blocked, you might have a rule that blocks everything. If you only test safe commands pass, you might have no blocking at all.

```rust
/// Tier 1 - Microcompact: replace old tool_result content with placeholders.
/// Keeps the last 3 tool results intact. Preserves file_read results always.
pub fn micro_compact(messages: &mut Vec<Message>) -> usize {
    // Collect indices of all tool-result messages
    let tool_result_indices: Vec<usize> = messages
        .iter()
        .enumerate()
        .filter(|(_, m)| m.role == Role::Tool)
        .map(|(i, _)| i)
        .collect();

    // Keep the last 3 intact
    if tool_result_indices.len() <= 3 {
        return 0;
    }
    let cutoff = tool_result_indices.len() - 3;
    let mut compacted = 0;

    for &idx in &tool_result_indices[..cutoff] {
        let msg = &messages[idx];

        // Already compacted - skip
        if msg.content.starts_with("[Previous: used ") {
            continue;
        }

        // Resolve tool name from the matching assistant tool_call
        let tool_name = if let Some(ref tc_id) = msg.tool_call_id {
            find_tool_name_for_call(messages, tc_id, idx)
        } else {
            None
        };
        let tool_name = tool_name.unwrap_or_else(|| "tool".to_string());

        // Exception: preserve file_read results (reference material)
        if tool_name == "file_read" {
            continue;
        }

        messages[idx].content = format!("[Previous: used {tool_name}]");
        compacted += 1;
    }

    compacted
}

fn find_tool_name_for_call(messages: &[Message], call_id: &str, before_idx: usize) -> Option<String> {
    for msg in messages[..before_idx].iter().rev() {
        if msg.role == Role::Assistant {
            if let Some(ref calls) = msg.tool_calls {
                for tc in calls {
                    if tc.id == call_id {
                        return Some(tc.name.clone());
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
    None
}
```

Why preserve file_read: the model references file contents when making edits. If you compact away a file_read result, the model will either re-read the file (wasting a tool call) or hallucinate the contents. Bash output and grep results are ephemeral; file contents are structural.

The attack scenario: a locally-running LLM generates a tool call with a fabricated tool name like `exec` or `eval`, or uses a homoglyph character to make `bash` look like `bash` (with Cyrillic 'a'). Without strict validation against a registry, unregistered tools could be dispatched.

```rust
use std::collections::HashMap;
use serde_json::Value;

#[derive(Debug, PartialEq)]
pub enum ValidationResult {
    Valid,
    UnknownTool(String),
    MissingParam(String),
    InvalidParamType { param: String, expected: String, got: String },
}

pub struct ToolCallValidator {
    schemas: HashMap<String, Value>,
}

impl ToolCallValidator {
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        Self { schemas: HashMap::new() }
    }

    pub fn register_tool(&mut self, name: &str, schema: &Value) {
        self.schemas.insert(name.to_string(), schema.clone());
    }

    pub fn validate(&self, call: &ParsedToolCall) -> ValidationResult {
        // Strict name lookup -- no fuzzy matching, no Unicode normalization
        let schema = match self.schemas.get(&call.name) {
            Some(s) => s,
            None => return ValidationResult::UnknownTool(call.name.clone()),
        };

        // Check required parameters
        if let Some(required) = schema.get("required").and_then(|r| r.as_array()) {
            for req in required {
                if let Some(param_name) = req.as_str() {
                    if !call.arguments.contains_key(param_name) {
                        return ValidationResult::MissingParam(param_name.to_string());
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        // Check parameter types against schema
        if let Some(properties) = schema.get("properties").and_then(|p| p.as_object()) {
            for (key, value) in &call.arguments {
                if let Some(prop_schema) = properties.get(key) {
                    if let Some(expected_type) = prop_schema.get("type").and_then(|t| t.as_str()) {
                        if !types_compatible(expected_type, value) {
                            return ValidationResult::InvalidParamType {
                                param: key.clone(),
                                expected: expected_type.to_string(),
                                got: json_type_name(value).to_string(),
                            };
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        ValidationResult::Valid
    }
}

fn types_compatible(expected: &str, value: &Value) -> bool {
    match expected {
        "string" => value.is_string(),
        "integer" | "number" => value.is_number(),
        "boolean" => value.is_boolean(),
        "object" => value.is_object(),
        "array" => value.is_array(),
        _ => true,
    }
}

fn json_type_name(v: &Value) -> &str {
    match v {
        Value::String(_) => "string",
        Value::Number(_) => "number",
        Value::Bool(_) => "boolean",
        Value::Object(_) => "object",
        Value::Array(_) => "array",
        Value::Null => "null",
    }
}
```

Critical: the validator uses exact string matching for tool names. This means Cyrillic homoglyphs (`b\u{0430}sh`) and zero-width characters (`ba\u{200B}sh`) are automatically rejected as unknown tools without any special handling.

Stop using `unwrap()` immediately -- it panics on failure and crashes your program. Use the `anyhow` crate for application-level error handling.

**Wrong way:**
```rust
fn load_config(path: &str) -> Config {
    let contents = std::fs::read_to_string(path).unwrap();
    let config: Config = serde_json::from_str(&contents).unwrap();
    config
}
```
This panics with an unhelpful message if the file is missing or the JSON is malformed.

**Idiomatic way:**
```rust
use anyhow::{Context, Result};

fn load_config(path: &str) -> Result<Config> {
    let contents = std::fs::read_to_string(path)
        .with_context(|| format!("Failed to read config from {path}"))?;
    let config: Config = serde_json::from_str(&contents)
        .with_context(|| format!("Invalid JSON in {path}"))?;
    Ok(config)
}
```

Key points:
- `Result` from anyhow is `Result<T, anyhow::Error>` -- it can hold any error type
- The `?` operator propagates errors up the call stack
- `.with_context()` adds human-readable context to the error chain
- The caller gets a full error chain: `"Invalid JSON in config.toml: expected value at line 3 column 1"`

It depends on the access pattern. `unsafe impl Send` promises that the type is safe to transfer to another thread, but NOT that it's safe to share between threads simultaneously. The critical question: will two threads ever access the same context at the same time?

For llama.cpp, the answer is no -- a single inference context should be driven by one thread at a time. The unsafe Send is acceptable with a documented invariant:

```rust
pub struct LlamaContext {
    ctx: *mut llama_context,
    model: *mut llama_model,
}

// SAFETY: LlamaContext is safe to transfer between threads.
// Invariant: one Sampler drives one context sequentially.
// The caller must ensure no concurrent access to the same context.
unsafe impl Send for LlamaContext {}

impl Drop for LlamaContext {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        // Null-check before free to prevent double-free
        if !self.ctx.is_null() {
            unsafe { llama_free(self.ctx); }
            self.ctx = std::ptr::null_mut();
        }
        if !self.model.is_null() {
            unsafe { llama_free_model(self.model); }
            self.model = std::ptr::null_mut();
        }
    }
}
```

Red test to document the guarantee:

```rust
#[test]
fn test_p1_llama_context_is_send() {
    fn assert_send<T: Send>() {}
    assert_send::<LlamaContext>();
}
```

The null check in Drop prevents double-free. If Drop runs twice (which Rust prevents, but defensive coding is good), the second call is a no-op.

If you want to enforce single-threaded access at the type level, wrap it in a `Mutex`:

```rust
use std::sync::Mutex;

pub struct SafeLlamaContext(Mutex<LlamaContext>);

impl SafeLlamaContext {
    pub fn with_context<R>(&self, f: impl FnOnce(&mut LlamaContext) -> R) -> R {
        let mut ctx = self.0.lock().unwrap();
        f(&mut ctx)
    }
}
```

This makes the invariant enforceable by the compiler rather than relying on documentation.

Yes. `CString::new()` rejects strings with interior null bytes by returning `Err(NulError)`. This is the correct defense against null byte injection in FFI paths.

