Split compound commands on `&&`, `||`, `;`, and `|`, respecting quotes, then classify each segment independently. The final tier is the worst of all segments:

```rust
fn split_compound_command(cmd: &str) -> Vec<String> {
    let mut segments = Vec::new();
    let mut current = String::new();
    let mut chars = cmd.chars().peekable();
    let mut in_single_quote = false;
    let mut in_double_quote = false;

    while let Some(c) = chars.next() {
        match c {
            '\'' if !in_double_quote => {
                in_single_quote = !in_single_quote;
                current.push(c);
            }
            '"' if !in_single_quote => {
                in_double_quote = !in_double_quote;
                current.push(c);
            }
            '&' if !in_single_quote && !in_double_quote => {
                if chars.peek() == Some(&'&') {
                    chars.next();
                    segments.push(current.clone());
                    current.clear();
                } else {
                    current.push(c);
                }
            }
            '|' if !in_single_quote && !in_double_quote => {
                if chars.peek() == Some(&'|') { chars.next(); }
                segments.push(current.clone());
                current.clear();
            }
            ';' if !in_single_quote && !in_double_quote => {
                segments.push(current.clone());
                current.clear();
            }
            _ => current.push(c),
        }
    }
    if !current.trim().is_empty() { segments.push(current); }
    segments
}

fn worse_tier(a: PermissionTier, b: PermissionTier) -> PermissionTier {
    match (a, b) {
        (PermissionTier::Destructive, _) | (_, PermissionTier::Destructive) => PermissionTier::Destructive,
        (PermissionTier::Write, _) | (_, PermissionTier::Write) => PermissionTier::Write,
        _ => PermissionTier::Safe,
    }
}
```

So `ls | grep foo` splits to [`ls`, `grep foo`] -> both Safe -> Safe.
`ls && rm file.txt` splits to [`ls`, `rm file.txt`] -> Safe + Destructive -> Destructive.

The quote tracking prevents splitting inside string arguments like `echo "hello && world"`.

```rust
pub async fn process_tool_calls(
    tool_calls: &[ToolCall],
    registry: &ToolRegistry,
    config: &Config,
    grant_cache: &GrantCache,
    ctx: &ToolContext,
) -> Vec<Message> {
    let mut results = Vec::new();

    for tc in tool_calls {
        // Step 1: Hard block check (non-negotiable)
        if let Some(reason) = hard_block_check(&tc.name, &tc.arguments) {
            results.push(Message {
                role: Role::Tool,
                content: format!("BLOCKED: {reason}"),
                tool_call_id: Some(tc.id.clone()),
                tool_calls: None,
            });
            continue;
        }

        // Step 2: Classify permission tier
        let tier = classify(&tc.name, &tc.arguments);

        // Step 3: Check against mode and grants
        let verdict = check_permission(
            tier, &config.permissions.mode, grant_cache, &tc.name, &tc.arguments
        );

        match verdict {
            PermissionVerdict::Blocked(reason) => {
                results.push(Message {
                    role: Role::Tool,
                    content: format!("PERMISSION DENIED: {reason}"),
                    tool_call_id: Some(tc.id.clone()),
                    tool_calls: None,
                });
            }
            PermissionVerdict::NeedsConfirmation(desc) => {
                // Ask user via TUI - if denied, return error
                let approved = ask_user_confirmation(&desc).await;
                if !approved {
                    results.push(Message {
                        role: Role::Tool,
                        content: "User denied permission".to_string(),
                        tool_call_id: Some(tc.id.clone()),
                        tool_calls: None,
                    });
                    continue;
                }
                // Fall through to execution
                let result = registry.execute(&tc.name, tc.arguments.clone(), ctx).await;
                results.push(tool_result_to_message(&tc.id, result));
            }
            PermissionVerdict::Approved => {
                let result = registry.execute(&tc.name, tc.arguments.clone(), ctx).await;
                results.push(tool_result_to_message(&tc.id, result));
            }
        }
    }

    results
}

fn tool_result_to_message(call_id: &str, result: Result<ToolResult>) -> Message {
    let (content, is_error) = match result {
        Ok(tr) => (tr.output, tr.is_error),
        Err(e) => (format!("Error: {e}"), true),
    };
    Message {
        role: Role::Tool,
        content,
        tool_call_id: Some(call_id.to_string()),
        tool_calls: None,
    }
}
```

Errors from tool execution become tool result messages, not application crashes. The model sees `Error: file not found` and decides what to do next. This is essential for the agent loop pattern where the model self-corrects.

The pipeline order matters: hard blocks first (cheapest check, non-negotiable), then tier classification, then permission verdict. Each step can short-circuit the pipeline.

