This has a P0 arbitrary file write vulnerability via supply chain attack (OWASP A08:2021).

**Attack scenario:** An attacker publishes a model on HuggingFace with a crafted `model.safetensors.index.json` containing:
```json
{"weight_map": {"layer.0.weight": "../../../.ssh/authorized_keys"}}
```

When `model_dir.join("../../../.ssh/authorized_keys")` resolves, it escapes the model directory and writes the downloaded content (which the attacker controls) to the victim's SSH authorized_keys, granting SSH access.

Other payloads:
- `../../.bashrc` -- inject shell commands
- `../../../etc/cron.d/backdoor` -- persistent access
- `subfolder/../../escape.bin` -- sneaky nested traversal

Fix:

```rust
fn validate_shard_filename(shard: &str) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    if shard.contains("..") {
        anyhow::bail!("path traversal in shard filename: {shard}");
    }
    if shard.starts_with('/') || shard.starts_with('\\') {
        anyhow::bail!("absolute path in shard filename: {shard}");
    }
    if shard.contains('\0') {
        anyhow::bail!("null byte in shard filename: {shard}");
    }
    if !shard.chars().all(|c| c.is_alphanumeric() || "-_.".contains(c)) {
        anyhow::bail!("disallowed characters in shard: {shard}");
    }
    Ok(())
}

fn process_weight_map(model_dir: &Path, weight_map: &HashMap<String, String>) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    for (_tensor, shard_file) in weight_map {
        validate_shard_filename(shard_file)?;
        let dest = model_dir.join(shard_file);
        download_file(&format!("https://hf.co/model/{}", shard_file), &dest)?;
    }
    Ok(())
}

#[test]
fn test_p0_shard_traversal_blocked() {
    assert!(validate_shard_filename("../../../.ssh/authorized_keys").is_err());
    assert!(validate_shard_filename("../../.bashrc").is_err());
    assert!(validate_shard_filename("subfolder/../../escape").is_err());
}

#[test]
fn test_legit_shards_pass() {
    assert!(validate_shard_filename("model-00001-of-00004.safetensors").is_ok());
    assert!(validate_shard_filename("config.json").is_ok());
}
```

This is a trust boundary issue: data from external sources (HuggingFace index files) is untrusted input that must be validated before filesystem operations. The character allowlist ensures only simple filenames are accepted.

Test with both matching and non-matching project paths to verify scoping works.

```rust
#[test]
fn test_rules_scope_matching() {
    let mut engine = RulesEngine::new();
    let project = PathBuf::from(env!("CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR"));
    let rules_text = format!(r#"
scope "{}" {{
  rule "no-force-push" {{
    on tool:git
    reject contains(command, "push --force")
    reason "No force pushes in this project"
  }}
}}
"#, project.display());
    engine.load(&rules_text).unwrap();

    let mut ctx = EvalContext::new(RuleEvent::Tool("git".to_string()));
    ctx.set_str("command", "push --force origin main");

    // Matching project path -> should reject
    let result = engine.evaluate(&ctx, Some(&project.to_string_lossy()));
    assert!(matches!(result, RuleAction::Reject(_)));
}

#[test]
fn test_rules_scope_no_match() {
    let mut engine = RulesEngine::new();
    engine.load(r#"
scope "/some/other/project" {
  rule "no-force-push" {
    on tool:git
    reject contains(command, "push --force")
    reason "No force pushes"
  }
}
"#).unwrap();

    let mut ctx = EvalContext::new(RuleEvent::Tool("git".to_string()));
    ctx.set_str("command", "push --force origin main");

    // Different project path -> scope doesn't apply -> allow
    let result = engine.evaluate(&ctx, Some("/different/project"));
    assert!(matches!(result, RuleAction::Allow));
}
```

The two tests together prove that scope matching is both inclusive (matching path triggers the rule) and exclusive (non-matching path doesn't). Using `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR` for the matching test ensures the path is always valid on the test machine.

This is a critical concern. Your evolution system takes untrusted data (tool names, error messages, project names) from past sessions and interpolates them into DSL rule text. Each of these is an injection vector.

Here are the three P0 attack scenarios:

**1. Tool name injection into ordering rules.** If the system detects that `file_read` always precedes `file_edit`, it generates:
```
rule evo-order-file_read-before-file_edit {
  when sequence("file_read", "file_edit")
}
```
But if `tool_name = 'file_read")\n  reject "all_tools_blocked'`, the generated rule contains an injected `reject` directive.

**2. Error message injection into failure rules.** Error messages get embedded in reject directives. If `error = 'permission denied\n  reject "block_everything"\n}'`, the error text breaks out of its string context and injects a new rule block.

**3. Project name injection into scope directives.** The project name goes into `scope "project_name"`. A malicious project name like `proj"\n}\nrule evil {\n  scope "*"\n  reject "all"` injects an entirely new rule.

Red tests for each:

```rust
#[test]
fn test_p0_dsl_injection_via_tool_name() {
    let evil_tool = "file_read\")\n  reject \"all_tools_blocked";
    // Feed 7+ sessions with this tool name to trigger pattern detection
    for i in 0..8 {
        let outcome = make_outcome(&format!("s{i}"), "proj", OutcomeType::Success,
            vec![(evil_tool, ToolResultType::Success), ("file_edit", ToolResultType::Success)]);
        engine.analyze_and_evolve(&outcome).unwrap();
    }
    let rules = engine.analyze_and_evolve(&final_outcome).unwrap();
    for rule in &rules {
        assert!(!rule.ftai_rule.contains("reject \"all_tools_blocked"),
            "DSL injection via tool name! Rule: {}", rule.ftai_rule);
        assert!(!rule.name.contains('\n'),
            "Newline in rule name indicates injection");
    }
}
```

The fix: sanitize all interpolated values. Strip or reject strings containing quotes, braces, newlines, and backslashes before they enter DSL templates. For error messages, escape backslashes BEFORE escaping quotes (otherwise `\"` becomes `\\"` which re-opens the quote).

Absolutely. The evolution store persists session outcomes, tool call records, and generated rules to SQLite. Every text field is an injection surface.

Attack scenarios:
- Task description: `'; DROP TABLE sessions; --`
- Error message from a tool: `error: '; DROP TABLE tool_calls; --`
- Tool name: `'; DELETE FROM tool_calls; --`
- Generated rule name: `'; DROP TABLE generated_rules; --`
- Generated rule content: `rule x { '; DROP TABLE generated_rules; -- }`

All of these must use parameterized queries:

```rust
#[test]
fn test_p0_sql_injection_via_task_description() {
    let store = test_store();
    let outcome = sample_outcome("s1", "proj",
        "'; DROP TABLE sessions; --",  // malicious task description
        OutcomeType::Success,
        vec![("file_read", ToolResultType::Success)]);
    store.save_outcome(&outcome).unwrap();

    let loaded = store.recent_sessions(10).unwrap();
    assert_eq!(loaded.len(), 1);
    assert_eq!(loaded[0].task_description, "'; DROP TABLE sessions; --");
}

#[test]
fn test_p0_sql_injection_via_rule_name() {
    let store = test_store();
    let rule = GeneratedRule {
        name: "'; DROP TABLE generated_rules; --".to_string(),
        source: RuleSource::OrderingPattern,
        confidence: 0.9,
        ftai_rule: "rule x { }".to_string(),
    };
    store.save_generated_rule(&rule).unwrap();

    let active = store.active_rules().unwrap();
    assert_eq!(active.len(), 1);
    assert_eq!(active[0].name, "'; DROP TABLE generated_rules; --");
}
```

There's also a second-order concern: `active_rules()` loads rule text from the database and returns it to the rule evaluator. If an attacker can write to the SQLite file (local access), they can insert rules with `reject "*"` that block all tool calls. The rule evaluator should validate loaded rules before applying them -- check brace balance, restrict to known directives, and cap rule count.

```rust
pub struct DreamRunner {
    project_path: PathBuf,
    dream_dir: PathBuf,
    transcripts_dir: PathBuf,
    memory_dir: PathBuf,
}

impl DreamRunner {
    pub fn new(project_path: &Path) -> Self {
        let ftai = project_path.join(".ftai");
        Self {
            project_path: project_path.to_path_buf(),
            dream_dir: ftai.join("dreams"),
            transcripts_dir: ftai.join("transcripts"),
            memory_dir: ftai.join("memory"),
        }
    }

    pub fn run(&self, since_time: Option<u64>) -> Result<PathBuf> {
        self.validate_paths()?; // all paths must be inside .ftai
        std::fs::create_dir_all(&self.dream_dir)?;
        std::fs::create_dir_all(&self.memory_dir)?;

        // Phase 1: Orient - read existing memories
        let existing = self.phase1_orient();

        // Phase 2: Gather signal from transcripts
        let signal = self.phase2_gather_signal(since_time.unwrap_or(0));
        if signal.session_count == 0 {
            // Write empty dream and return
            let path = self.dream_dir.join("latest.md");
            std::fs::write(&path, "No sessions found since last dream.")?;
            return Ok(path);
        }

        // Phase 3: Consolidate memory (hot files, repeated errors)
        let memory_updates = self.phase3_consolidate_memory(&signal, &existing)?;

        // Phase 4: Analyze unresolved error patterns
        let analyses = self.phase4_analyze(&signal)?;

        // Phase 5: Write latest.md summary
        self.phase5_write_summary(&signal, &memory_updates, &analyses)
    }

    fn phase2_gather_signal(&self, since_time: u64) -> Signal {
        let mut signal = Signal::default();
        for entry in std::fs::read_dir(&self.transcripts_dir).into_iter().flatten().flatten() {
            let path = entry.path();
            if path.extension().map_or(true, |e| e != "jsonl") { continue; }
            // Security: canonical path must be inside transcripts_dir
            if let Ok(canonical) = path.canonicalize() {
                if let Ok(canon_dir) = self.transcripts_dir.canonicalize() {
                    if !canonical.starts_with(&canon_dir) { continue; }
                }
            }
            // Parse JSONL, extract tool counts, file counts, errors, topics
            if let Ok(content) = std::fs::read_to_string(&path) {
                for line in content.lines() {
                    if let Ok(msg) = serde_json::from_str::<Value>(line) {
                        self.extract_from_message(&msg, &mut signal);
                    }
                }
                signal.session_count += 1;
            }
        }
        signal
    }

    fn phase3_consolidate_memory(&self, signal: &Signal, _: &[(String, String)]) -> Result<Vec<String>> {
        let mut updates = Vec::new();
        // Write hot-files.md for files edited >= 3 times
        let hot: Vec<_> = signal.file_counts.iter().filter(|(_, c)| **c >= 3).collect();
        if !hot.is_empty() {
            let content = hot.iter().map(|(p, c)| format!("- {p} ({c} edits)")).collect::<Vec<_>>().join("\n");
            std::fs::write(self.memory_dir.join("hot-files.md"), content)?;
            updates.push("Updated: hot-files".into());
        }
        Ok(updates)
    }
}
```

The dream is injected into the next session if it's < 48 hours old:
```rust
pub fn dream_context_for_session(project_path: &Path) -> Option<String> {
    let path = project_path.join(".ftai/dreams/latest.md");
    let age = path.metadata().ok()?.modified().ok()
        .and_then(|t| SystemTime::now().duration_since(t).ok())?;
    if age.as_secs() > 48 * 60 * 60 { return None; }
    std::fs::read_to_string(&path).ok().filter(|s| !s.trim().is_empty())
}
```

The 48-hour TTL prevents stale dreams from polluting new sessions. The 5-phase pipeline is deterministic (no model calls), so it runs instantly as a post-session hook.

```rust
use anyhow::{Context, Result};
use std::path::{Path, PathBuf};

pub struct LoadedPlugin {
    pub manifest: PluginManifest,
    pub dir: PathBuf,
}

pub struct PluginManager {
    plugins_dir: PathBuf,
    plugins: Vec<LoadedPlugin>,
}

impl PluginManager {
    pub fn new(plugins_dir: PathBuf) -> Self {
        Self { plugins_dir, plugins: Vec::new() }
    }

    pub fn load_all(&mut self) -> Result<usize> {
        self.plugins.clear();
        if !self.plugins_dir.exists() { return Ok(0); }
        let entries = std::fs::read_dir(&self.plugins_dir)?;
        for entry in entries {
            let path = entry?.path();
            if !path.is_dir() { continue; }
            if !path.join("plugin.toml").exists() { continue; }
            match manifest::load_manifest(&path) {
                Ok(m) => self.plugins.push(LoadedPlugin { manifest: m, dir: path }),
                Err(e) => eprintln!("Warning: failed to load plugin at {}: {e}", path.display()),
            }
        }
        Ok(self.plugins.len())
    }

    pub fn uninstall(&mut self, name: &str) -> Result<()> {
        let dir = self.plugins_dir.join(name);
        if !dir.exists() { anyhow::bail!("Plugin '{name}' not installed"); }

        // Path traversal guard: canonicalize and verify containment
        let canonical_dir = dir.canonicalize()?;
        let canonical_plugins = self.plugins_dir.canonicalize()?;
        if !canonical_dir.starts_with(&canonical_plugins) {
            anyhow::bail!("Plugin path escapes plugins directory");
        }

        std::fs::remove_dir_all(&dir)?;
        self.plugins.retain(|p| p.manifest.plugin.name != name);
        Ok(())
    }

    pub fn get_tools(&self) -> Vec<PluginTool> {
        self.plugins.iter().flat_map(|plugin| {
            plugin.manifest.tools.iter().map(move |td| PluginTool::new(
                format!("plugin:{}:{}", plugin.manifest.plugin.name, td.name),
                td.description.clone(),
                td.command.clone(),
                plugin.dir.clone(),
                td.params.clone(),
            ))
        }).collect()
    }
}
```

The uninstall path traversal guard is critical: without `canonicalize()` + `starts_with()`, an attacker could call `uninstall("../important-data")` and delete arbitrary directories. The `plugin:` namespace prefix on tool names prevents plugins from impersonating built-in tools like `bash`.

Path traversal is a P0 vulnerability where an attacker supplies paths like `../../../etc/passwd` to escape the intended directory and read or write arbitrary files.

The attack scenario: an LLM-powered assistant receives a user request that causes it to call `file_read` with a path containing `..` sequences. Without validation, the tool reads `/etc/passwd` instead of staying within the project directory.

```rust
use std::path::{Path, PathBuf};

pub struct PathValidation {
    pub is_allowed: bool,
    pub reason: Option<String>,
}

pub fn validate_path(path: &str, operation: &str) -> PathValidation {
    // Reject empty paths
    if path.is_empty() {
        return PathValidation { is_allowed: false, reason: Some("Empty path".into()) };
    }
    // Reject null bytes (C-layer truncation attack)
    if path.contains('\0') {
        return PathValidation { is_allowed: false, reason: Some("Null byte in path".into()) };
    }
    // Reject parent traversal
    if path.contains("..") {
        return PathValidation { is_allowed: false, reason: Some("Path traversal blocked".into()) };
    }
    // Reject Unicode fullwidth traversal chars (U+FF0E = fullwidth period, U+FF0F = fullwidth slash)
    if path.contains('\u{FF0E}') || path.contains('\u{FF0F}') {
        return PathValidation { is_allowed: false, reason: Some("Unicode traversal characters".into()) };
    }
    // Block sensitive paths
    let blocked_prefixes = [
        "/etc", "/var", "/System", "/usr", "/tmp",
        "~/.ssh", "~/Library/Keychains", "~/Library/Cookies",
    ];
    let expanded = expand_tilde(path);
    for prefix in &blocked_prefixes {
        let expanded_prefix = expand_tilde(prefix);
        if expanded.starts_with(&expanded_prefix) {
            return PathValidation {
                is_allowed: false,
                reason: Some(format!("Access to {} is blocked", prefix)),
            };
        }
    }
    // Block delete on home directory root
    if operation == "delete" {
        let home = dirs::home_dir().unwrap_or_default();
        if expanded == home.to_string_lossy() {
            return PathValidation { is_allowed: false, reason: Some("Cannot delete home directory".into()) };
        }
    }
    PathValidation { is_allowed: true, reason: None }
}
```

Red test methodology: write tests for each attack vector (traversal, null bytes, Unicode tricks, sensitive paths), assert they are blocked, then verify legitimate paths like `~/Documents/notes.txt` still pass.

URL scheme validation is P0 because `javascript:` URLs execute arbitrary code in the browser context, and `file:` URLs expose the local filesystem. The attack scenario: the LLM is instructed to open `javascript:alert(document.cookie)` which steals session cookies, or `file:///etc/passwd` which reads system files.

```rust
use url::Url;

#[derive(Debug, PartialEq)]
pub enum UrlValidation {
    Allowed,
    Blocked(String),
}

pub fn validate_url(raw: &str) -> UrlValidation {
    if raw.is_empty() {
        return UrlValidation::Blocked("empty URL".into());
    }

    // Parse the URL to extract scheme reliably
    let parsed = match Url::parse(raw) {
        Ok(u) => u,
        Err(_) => return UrlValidation::Blocked("invalid URL".into()),
    };

    let scheme = parsed.scheme().to_lowercase();

    // Allowlist of safe schemes
    let allowed_schemes = ["http", "https"];
    if !allowed_schemes.contains(&scheme.as_str()) {
        return UrlValidation::Blocked(format!("blocked scheme: {scheme}"));
    }

    // Length check to prevent DoS
    if raw.len() > 100_000 {
        return UrlValidation::Blocked("URL too long".into());
    }

    UrlValidation::Allowed
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn test_javascript_scheme_blocked() {
        assert_eq!(
            validate_url("javascript:alert(document.cookie)"),
            UrlValidation::Blocked("blocked scheme: javascript".into())
        );
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_file_scheme_blocked() {
        assert_eq!(
            validate_url("file:///etc/passwd"),
            UrlValidation::Blocked("blocked scheme: file".into())
        );
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_data_scheme_blocked() {
        assert_eq!(
            validate_url("data:text/html,<script>alert('xss')</script>"),
            UrlValidation::Blocked("blocked scheme: data".into())
        );
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_https_allowed() {
        assert_eq!(validate_url("https://example.com"), UrlValidation::Allowed);
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_empty_url_blocked() {
        assert_eq!(validate_url(""), UrlValidation::Blocked("empty URL".into()));
    }
}
```

Use an allowlist (http, https only), not a blocklist. A blocklist would miss new schemes like `vbscript:`, `blob:`, or custom app schemes. The `url` crate handles scheme parsing correctly even with unusual casing or whitespace.

Use `@Published` properties for SwiftUI binding and an async token stream:

```swift
@MainActor
public class ChatManager: ObservableObject {
    @Published public var streamingResponse: String = ""
    @Published public var isStreaming: Bool = false

    func processStreamingResponse(stream: AsyncStream<String>) async {
        isStreaming = true
        streamingResponse = ""

        for await token in stream {
            streamingResponse += token
        }

        // Stream complete -- finalize the message
        let finalContent = streamingResponse
        streamingResponse = ""
        isStreaming = false

        // Append to conversation
        var conversation = currentConversation!
        conversation.messages.append(Message(content: finalContent, role: .assistant))
        currentConversation = conversation
    }
}
```

Key points: (1) All UI state updates happen on `@MainActor`. (2) `streamingResponse` is a separate published property from the final message list so the UI can show a live typing indicator. (3) Clear `streamingResponse` when done and append to the actual conversation. (4) The `isStreaming` flag lets the UI disable input and show an animation. (5) Token-by-token updates are throttled by SwiftUI's view update batching automatically.

```rust
use serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};
use std::collections::HashMap;
use std::path::Path;
use std::time::{SystemTime, UNIX_EPOCH};

/// Structured session state that survives total context loss.
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Serialize, Deserialize)]
pub struct SessionCheckpoint {
    pub timestamp: u64,
    pub files_modified: Vec<String>,
    pub tools_used: Vec<(String, usize)>,
    pub errors_encountered: Vec<String>,
    pub last_user_request: Option<String>,
    pub pending_work: Option<String>,
}

pub fn extract_session_memory(messages: &[Message], project_path: &Path) -> Result<PathBuf> {
    let checkpoint = SessionCheckpoint {
        timestamp: SystemTime::now().duration_since(UNIX_EPOCH)
            .unwrap_or_default().as_secs(),
        files_modified: extract_modified_files(messages),
        tools_used: extract_tool_usage(messages),
        errors_encountered: extract_errors(messages),
        last_user_request: extract_last_user_message(messages),
        pending_work: extract_pending_work(messages),
    };

    let dir = project_path.join(".ftai").join("checkpoints");
    std::fs::create_dir_all(&dir)?;
    let path = dir.join(format!("{}.json", checkpoint.timestamp));
    std::fs::write(&path, serde_json::to_string_pretty(&checkpoint)?)?;
    Ok(path)
}

fn extract_modified_files(messages: &[Message]) -> Vec<String> {
    let mut files = Vec::new();
    for msg in messages {
        if let Some(ref calls) = msg.tool_calls {
            for tc in calls {
                if tc.name == "file_write" || tc.name == "file_edit" {
                    if let Some(path) = tc.arguments.get("path").and_then(|v| v.as_str()) {
                        if !files.contains(&path.to_string()) {
                            files.push(path.to_string());
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
    files
}

fn extract_tool_usage(messages: &[Message]) -> Vec<(String, usize)> {
    let mut counts: HashMap<String, usize> = HashMap::new();
    for msg in messages {
        if let Some(ref calls) = msg.tool_calls {
            for tc in calls { *counts.entry(tc.name.clone()).or_default() += 1; }
        }
    }
    let mut result: Vec<_> = counts.into_iter().collect();
    result.sort_by(|a, b| b.1.cmp(&a.1));
    result
}
```

This checkpoint gets written to disk before Tier 3 compaction. After the context is cleared and reinjected with the summary, the model can read the checkpoint via `file_read` to recover exact file paths it was editing, the last user request, and any errors it was debugging.

For a stateless classifier, use free functions in a module. Reserve methods for when the function needs `&self` state.

**Over-engineered (unnecessary struct):**
```rust
struct PermissionClassifier;

impl PermissionClassifier {
    fn classify(&self, tool_name: &str, params: &Value) -> PermissionTier {
        // ...
    }
}
// Caller: PermissionClassifier.classify(name, params) -- useless indirection
```

**Idiomatic -- free functions in a module:**
```rust
// permissions/classifier.rs
pub fn classify(tool_name: &str, params: &Value) -> PermissionTier {
    match tool_name {
        "file_read" | "glob" | "grep" => PermissionTier::Safe,
        "file_write" | "file_edit" => PermissionTier::Write,
        "bash" => classify_bash(params),
        "git" => classify_git(params),
        _ => PermissionTier::Write,
    }
}

pub fn hard_block_check(tool_name: &str, params: &Value) -> Option<String> { ... }
pub fn check_permission(tier: PermissionTier, mode: &PermissionMode, ...) -> PermissionVerdict { ... }

fn classify_git(params: &Value) -> PermissionTier { ... }  // private helper
fn classify_bash(params: &Value) -> PermissionTier { ... } // private helper
```

The module IS the namespace. Callers write `classifier::classify(name, params)` which reads naturally. Use a struct only if you need to hold state (e.g., a grant cache, configuration).

