Use `.peekable()` on any iterator to get a `Peekable` that supports `.peek()` without consuming the element.

```rust
fn split_compound_command(cmd: &str) -> Vec<String> {
    let mut segments = Vec::new();
    let mut current = String::new();
    let mut chars = cmd.chars().peekable();
    let mut in_single_quote = false;
    let mut in_double_quote = false;

    while let Some(c) = chars.next() {
        match c {
            '\'' if !in_double_quote => {
                in_single_quote = !in_single_quote;
                current.push(c);
            }
            '"' if !in_single_quote => {
                in_double_quote = !in_double_quote;
                current.push(c);
            }
            '&' if !in_single_quote && !in_double_quote => {
                // Peek to distinguish & from &&
                if chars.peek() == Some(&'&') {
                    chars.next(); // consume second &
                    segments.push(current.clone());
                    current.clear();
                } else {
                    current.push(c); // background operator, not &&
                }
            }
            '|' if !in_single_quote && !in_double_quote => {
                if chars.peek() == Some(&'|') {
                    chars.next(); // consume second |
                }
                segments.push(current.clone());
                current.clear();
            }
            ';' if !in_single_quote && !in_double_quote => {
                segments.push(current.clone());
                current.clear();
            }
            _ => current.push(c),
        }
    }

    if !current.trim().is_empty() {
        segments.push(current);
    }
    segments
}
```

`chars.peek() == Some(&'&')` checks the next character without consuming it. If it matches, `chars.next()` consumes it. This two-character lookahead pattern is essential for parsing `&&` vs `&`, `||` vs `|`, etc.

Chain strategies in order of lightest fix to heaviest, returning on first success.

```rust
pub enum RecoveryResult {
    Parsed(Vec<ParsedToolCall>),
    Failed { attempts: Vec<String>, original: String },
}

pub struct RecoveryPipeline {
    adapter: Box<dyn ToolCallAdapter>,
}

impl RecoveryPipeline {
    pub fn new(adapter: Box<dyn ToolCallAdapter>) -> Self {
        Self { adapter }
    }

    pub fn attempt_parse(&self, raw: &str) -> RecoveryResult {
        let mut attempts = Vec::new();

        // Strategy 1: Parse as-is
        if let Some(calls) = self.try_parse(raw) {
            return RecoveryResult::Parsed(calls);
        }
        attempts.push("direct parse".into());

        // Strategy 2: Close unclosed tags
        let repaired = self.close_unclosed_tags(raw);
        if let Some(calls) = self.try_parse(&repaired) {
            return RecoveryResult::Parsed(calls);
        }
        attempts.push("close unclosed tags".into());

        // Strategy 3: Strip surrounding text, extract XML block
        let extracted = self.extract_xml_block(raw);
        if let Some(calls) = self.try_parse(&extracted) {
            return RecoveryResult::Parsed(calls);
        }
        attempts.push("extract XML block".into());

        RecoveryResult::Failed {
            attempts,
            original: raw.to_string(),
        }
    }
}
```

