AppleScript injection is a P0 vulnerability because AppleScript can execute arbitrary shell commands via `do shell script`. The attack scenario: user asks the assistant to create a note titled `My Note" & do shell script "rm -rf /" & "`. When interpolated into `make new note with properties {name:"<TITLE>"}`, the quotes break out of the string literal and the `do shell script` executes.

Sanitization must handle: (1) double quotes, (2) backslashes (which can escape the escape), (3) newlines (which break AppleScript string context), (4) null bytes, (5) Unicode fullwidth quotes, (6) length limits.

```rust
pub fn sanitize_for_applescript(input: &str) -> String {
    let mut s = input.to_string();

    // Remove null bytes
    s = s.replace('\0', "");

    // Remove newlines and carriage returns (break string context)
    s = s.replace('\n', " ");
    s = s.replace('\r', "");

    // Normalize Unicode fullwidth quotes (U+FF02) to regular quotes
    s = s.replace('\u{FF02}', "\"");

    // Escape backslashes FIRST (before escaping quotes)
    // Otherwise: input `test\"` -> escape quotes -> `test\\"` -> broken
    s = s.replace('\\', "\\\\");

    // Then escape double quotes
    s = s.replace('"', "\\\"");

    // Truncate to prevent DoS (AppleScript has practical limits)
    if s.len() > 10_000 {
        s.truncate(10_000);
    }

    s
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn test_applescript_breakout_blocked() {
        let input = r#"My Note" & do shell script "whoami" & ""#;
        let sanitized = sanitize_for_applescript(input);
        // Count unescaped quotes: should be zero
        let chars: Vec<char> = sanitized.chars().collect();
        for (i, &c) in chars.iter().enumerate() {
            if c == '"' && (i == 0 || chars[i - 1] != '\\') {
                panic!("Unescaped quote at position {i} in: {sanitized}");
            }
        }
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_newline_injection_stripped() {
        let input = "line1\ntell application \"Terminal\"\ndo shell script \"whoami\"";
        let sanitized = sanitize_for_applescript(input);
        assert!(!sanitized.contains('\n'));
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_null_byte_stripped() {
        let sanitized = sanitize_for_applescript("test\0payload");
        assert!(!sanitized.contains('\0'));
        assert!(sanitized.contains("test"));
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_backslash_quote_chain() {
        // Raw input: test\\" -- backslash-backslash-quote
        let input = "test\\\"";
        let sanitized = sanitize_for_applescript(input);
        // All quotes must be escaped
        assert!(!has_unescaped_quote(&sanitized));
    }
}
```

The order matters: escape backslashes before quotes. If reversed, the backslash in `\"` gets doubled to `\\"`, which looks like an escaped backslash followed by a bare quote.

Use a three-tier compaction system with increasing aggressiveness:

**Tier 1 (Microcompact)** - runs before every LLM call, zero cost:
```rust
pub fn micro_compact(messages: &mut Vec<Message>) -> usize {
    let tool_indices: Vec<usize> = messages.iter().enumerate()
        .filter(|(_, m)| m.role == Role::Tool)
        .map(|(i, _)| i).collect();
    if tool_indices.len() <= 3 { return 0; }
    // Replace old tool results with one-liners
    // Exception: keep file_read results (model needs them for edits)
    // ...
}
```

**Tier 2 (Snip)** - at 70% context usage, remove oldest messages:
Save removed messages to a JSONL transcript first, insert a summary placeholder.

**Tier 3 (Summarize)** - at 85%, replace everything with a structured summary.

The trigger function:
```rust
pub fn should_compact(tokens: usize, max: usize) -> Option<u8> {
    let ratio = (tokens * 100) / max;
    if ratio > 95 { Some(5) }      // emergency
    else if ratio > 85 { Some(3) } // summarize
    else if ratio > 70 { Some(2) } // snip
    else { None }
}
```

Most sessions never leave Tier 1. The key insight is that tool results are the biggest space hog - a single `grep` or `bash` output can be thousands of tokens.

Two mechanisms handle this:

1. **Post-compaction reinjection**: After Tier 3 clears messages, the agent loop reinjects the system prompt components:
```rust
// After summarize_compact():
messages.push(build_identity_message());
messages.push(build_tool_definitions());
if let Some(rules) = rules_summary { messages.push(rules_message); }
if let Some(memory) = memory_context { messages.push(memory_message); }
```

2. **Session checkpoint** (Tier 4): Before Tier 3 fires, extract structured state to disk:
```rust
pub struct SessionCheckpoint {
    pub files_modified: Vec<String>,
    pub tools_used: Vec<(String, usize)>,
    pub errors_encountered: Vec<String>,
    pub last_user_request: Option<String>,
    pub pending_work: Option<String>,
}
```

The summary uses a 9-category structure (intent, technical concepts, files, errors, fixes, user messages, pending tasks, current work, next step) so the model knows exactly where it left off.

The checkpoint file lives at `.ftai/checkpoints/<timestamp>.json`. After reinjection, the model can `file_read` it to recover the exact state of what it was working on.

Split on whitespace and rejoin with single spaces. This defeats obfuscation via tabs and extra spaces.

```rust
fn normalize_bash(cmd: &str) -> String {
    cmd.split_whitespace().collect::<Vec<_>>().join(" ")
}
```

This collapses `"rm  -rf   /"` and `"rm\t-rf\t/"` both to `"rm -rf /"`, making pattern matching reliable.

Use it in hard-block checks:
```rust
pub fn hard_block_check(tool_name: &str, params: &Value) -> Option<String> {
    match tool_name {
        "bash" => {
            let command = params
                .get("command")
                .and_then(|v| v.as_str())
                .unwrap_or("");
            let normalized = normalize_bash(command);

            for blocked in HARD_BLOCKED_COMMANDS {
                if normalized.contains(blocked) {
                    return Some(format!("Hard-blocked command: {blocked}"));
                }
            }

            for pattern in HARD_BLOCKED_PATTERNS {
                if command.contains(pattern) {
                    return Some(format!("Hard-blocked pattern: fork bomb or equivalent"));
                }
            }
            None
        }
        _ => None,
    }
}
```

Note: fork bomb patterns like `:(){ :|:& };:` are checked against the original (unnormalized) command because their structure includes significant whitespace.
